#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:1
msgid "2.8 (2026-02-22)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:3
msgid "Support for Waf package types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:5
msgid "Introduction of the [`waf` package type](/guides/packages/pkg-type-waf). This new package type allow a developer to easily invoke Waf targets at various stages, without needing invoke these tools inside a scripts package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:9
msgid "Introduce package configurable maximum job limit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:11
msgid "This release introduces support for [`LIBFOO_MAX_JOBS`](pkg-opt-max-jobs), allowing a specific package to configure maximum number of jobs it should use for a build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:15
msgid "While [`LIBFOO_FIXED_JOBS`](pkg-opt-fixed-jobs) somewhat served this capability before, its use was tailored for restricting packages to a single job only. If a project could use a subset of jobs to run, there was no easy way to configure this. This could be tricky for packages which might have memory requirements per job unit which cannot be provided by a builder."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:21
msgid "If a build environment has tens to hundreds of cores, but a developer knows a package can only run around four jobs for package, they may tailor a maximum count as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:29
msgid "In addition to limiting job counts, the max-jobs value also accepts negative values. This can be used to hint to using N-less jobs than the detected amount. For example, if a package is best to use all cores but one for a build, a package may define negative one as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:38
msgid "Project configuration revisions options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:40
msgid "Packages will typically define revisions to fetch through [`LIBFOO_VERSION`](pkg-opt-version) and [`LIBFOO_REVISION`](pkg-opt-revision) options. This follows the idea of containing package-specific information inside a package's definition. However, developers may instead wish to manage fixed revisions in a single location due to their possible volatility when compared to other options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:47
msgid "Developers looking for the convenience of managing revisions in a single location can do so by defining a [`revisions`](conf-revisions) project configuration option. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:58
msgid "For the package `libfoo`, the its [`LIBFOO_REVISION`](pkg-opt-revision) will be configured to `libfoo-v2.1`. As well as the package `myapp` will have its [`MYAPP_REVISION`](pkg-opt-revision) configured to `1.0.0`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:62
msgid "Support skipping integrity checks for development-marked packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:64
msgid "Support has been added to allow developers to skip integrity checks for specific packages when in [development mode](/guides/development-mode)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:67
msgid "A package definition will typically have hashes defined for static resources to verify their contents. While this is desired approach for standard packages, a developer which defines a development-variant package when testing bleeding edge sources can experience fetch failures since development assets will have a mismatched hash. A developer can workaround this by appending additional hashes for a package, but this can remove the flexibility of acquiring bleeding edge assets for an internal package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:75
msgid "To workaround this scenario, the package configuration [`LIBFOO_DEVMODE_SKIP_INTEGRITY_CHECK`](pkg-opt-devmode-skip-integrity-check) has been introduced. Consider this example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:88
msgid "This package defines a default and development site for a package resource. If the package defined a hash file (`libfoo.hash`), the hash definition would typically require explicit hashes for both `libfoo-1.2.3.tar.gz` and `libfoo-latest.tar.gz`. However, if `LIBFOO_DEVMODE_SKIP_INTEGRITY_CHECK` is set, when running with in a `test` development mode, no hashes are required for the latest artifact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:95
msgid "SPDX license database updated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../content/news/2026-02-22_02.08.00.md:97
msgid "The internally managed copy of the [SPDX license identifiers][spdx] has been updated to the most recent version (v3.28)."
msgstr ""
